---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="Tire Pressure: Understanding PSI and Bar" description="Learn how to convert tire pressure between PSI and bar. Understand recommended pressures, why it matters for safety, and how to check your tires correctly." keywords="tire pressure, PSI to bar, tyre pressure conversion, car tire pressure, recommended tire pressure, bar to PSI, tire pressure guide">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Pressure</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">Tire Pressure: Understanding PSI and Bar</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">July 12, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>Your car manual says 32 PSI but the air pump at the petrol station shows bar. Or you are travelling abroad and need to inflate your tyres using unfamiliar units. Here is a straightforward guide to tyre pressure units and conversions.</p>

      <h2>The Conversion</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 bar = 14.504 PSI | 1 PSI = 0.0689 bar</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">Quick estimate: divide PSI by 14.5 to get bar, or multiply bar by 14.5 to get PSI</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Common Tyre Pressures Converted</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>28 PSI = 1.93 bar</li>
        <li>30 PSI = 2.07 bar</li>
        <li>32 PSI = 2.21 bar (most common for cars)</li>
        <li>34 PSI = 2.34 bar</li>
        <li>36 PSI = 2.48 bar</li>
        <li>40 PSI = 2.76 bar</li>
        <li>44 PSI = 3.03 bar</li>
        <li>80 PSI = 5.52 bar (bicycle tyres)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Where to Find Your Recommended Pressure</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Driver's door jamb:</strong> A sticker with recommended pressures for front and rear</li>
        <li><strong>Fuel filler cap:</strong> Some cars have the info here</li>
        <li><strong>Owner's manual:</strong> Lists pressures for different loads and tyre sizes</li>
        <li><strong>Never use the number on the tyre itself</strong> — that is the MAXIMUM pressure, not the recommended operating pressure</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Why Correct Pressure Matters</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Under-inflated:</strong> Increased fuel consumption (up to 3%), faster tyre wear on edges, risk of overheating and blowouts</li>
        <li><strong>Over-inflated:</strong> Reduced grip (less contact patch), harsher ride, uneven centre wear</li>
        <li><strong>Correct pressure:</strong> Even wear, optimal grip, best fuel economy, longer tyre life</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tips for Checking Tyre Pressure</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Check when cold</strong> — tyres gain 1-2 PSI for every 10 minutes of driving</li>
        <li><strong>Check monthly</strong> — tyres naturally lose 1-2 PSI per month</li>
        <li><strong>Include the spare</strong> — a flat spare is useless in an emergency</li>
        <li><strong>Adjust for load</strong> — fully loaded cars need higher pressure (check the door sticker for loaded values)</li>
        <li><strong>Temperature changes matter</strong> — pressure drops about 1 PSI for every 6°C (10°F) temperature drop</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/pressure" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Pressure Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/pressure" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
